  <prompt>
    REWRITE the `.claude/skills/jps-playbook-design/SKILL.md` body to reflect the R7 node-first dispatch
    model. This is the LARGEST skill (~25 KB) and arguably the most consequential â€” it teaches authors
    how to design end-to-end playbooks.

    Today this skill teaches authors to think "pick an Action; the Action's ActionType drives dispatch."
    After R7 the mental model is INVERTED: pick an Executor Type FIRST (the node's `sprk_executortype`
    Choice), then OPTIONALLY pick an Action (if the executor is prompt-driven â€” AiAnalysis / AiCompletion /
    AiEmbedding). Pure executors (Condition, Start, ReturnResponse, EntityNameValidator, CreateNotification,
    QueryDataverse, LookupUserMembership, etc.) have `sprk_actionid` NULL.

    Cite the Â§3.1 WHY (R3.1 history of dispatch-model confusion) so future authors understand WHY the
    mental model inverted, not just what changed.

    **Sub-Agent Write Boundary applies â€” main session executes this. No parallel dispatch.** Per CLAUDE.md Â§3,
    `.claude/skills/` writes happen only in main session.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior skill author for the Spaarke skill library. You understand the OLD playbook-design mental model
    (Action-first: pick an Action, the Action's ActionType determines runtime executor) and the NEW R7 model
    (Executor-first: pick an Executor Type Choice on the node, then optional Action if prompt-driven).
    Your job: rewrite the workflow steps so a future playbook author produces correct node configuration
    that survives the new single-hop dispatch.
  </role>

